</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#575757><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/ujinngersnapp.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Jinnger Snapp</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/white_fire.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Visitor</span><br>  Posts: 15<br> <font color=#E9D756>(11/9/01 3:11:52 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: EC Whores</span><hr size=1> Dracon, <br>
<br>
I think the real insult is not in implying they are lacking in characteristics that are associated with thier own gender but rather that an individual is displaying characteristics that are commonly associated with members of the other sex.  <br>
<br>
But the phrases 'like a girl' and 'like a man' are particularly indicative of the presumption that men are superior to women.  &quot;Like a girl&quot; implies weakness and inferiority.  &quot;Like a man&quot; implies strength and superiority.  Just think about when and how the phrases are used.<br>
<br>
Saying someone throws &quot;like a girl&quot; is insulting to women because it implies that girls cannot be and are not good athletes. It is insulting to men because it is saying that the man in question is &quot;like a girl&quot; in that he cannot be and is not a good athlete. <br>
<br>
If it the base belief was not that women were incapable of athleticism then the insult would have no power.<br>
<br>
Yes, we are all aware that the base assumption is not true. And most folk would interpret the phrasology simply as a slam on their strength and grace in throwing a ball. BUT the underlying assumption is still the gender equivalent of racism.<br>
<br>
The funny thing is that I am a girl and even I can get annoyed when someone tells me I throw 'like a girl'. Even when I know that there are innumerable examples of women who have strong arms. Such is the strength of the implication that girls are 'less than' boys.  go figure...<br>
<br>
Maybe I should buck up and take it &quot;like a man&quot;  <br>
<br>
Odd phrase that one, when there is so much evidence in history of womens ability to rise above adversity, struggle through harsh conditions, lead and survive to be victorious when faced with seemingly insurmountable odds.<br>
<br>
On second thought, I'd rather be 'like a girl'<br>
<br>
